processinfo.head: Processing Information
processinfo.p: The William Rose Benét Papers contains material acquired by the library with gifts from William Rose Benét, Marjorie Flack, and the estate of Marjorie Flack from 1948 through 1958. Manuscript material formerly classified as Za Benet and photographs and printed ephemera that had been cataloged separately were brought together and re-processed during 2016-2017.
Former call numbers: Za Benet, Za B437 +1, Za B437 +2, Za B437 +G1, and Za B437 +S1.

bioghist.head: William Rose Benét (1886-1950)
bioghist.p: William Rose Benét, born 2 February 1886 to James Walker Benét and Frances Rose (Neill) Benét, was an American poet, author, and editor who, along with his two siblings, Laura Benét and Stephen Vincent Benét, established the Benét family's literary reputation in the early through mid-twentieth century.

Benét was educated at Albany Academy before attending Yale College (1903-1907), where he served as editor of the Yale Courant and contributed to the Yale Record . After college, Benét went to work for Century Magazine as a reader. He served in the U.S. Air Services during the First World War, and after the war took work as a copy writer for an advertising firm. In 1920, Henry Seidel Canby brought Benét on as an assistant editor at the New York Evening Post . In 1923, Canby, Benét, and fellow editors Amy Loveman and Christopher Morley left the Post to form the Saturday Review , originally known as the Saturday Review of Literature .

Benét was the author of several collections of poetry, a novel, and a collection of essays. His autobiography in verse, The Dust Which Is God (1941), was awarded a Pulitzer Prize in 1942. In addition to his long-standing (1923-1950) position with the Saturday Review , Benét contributed to several compilations of English-language poetry and literature. Titles include The Oxford Anthology of American Literature and The Reader's Encyclopedia (1947).

Benét was married four times: first to Teresa Frances Thomson (1912-1919), with whom he had three children, then to the poet Elinor Wylie (1923-1928), to Lora Baxter (1932-1937), and lastly, to children's book author Majorie Flack (1941-1950).
Summary information is also available in the standard print and online biographical resources.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The William Rose Benét papers consist of correspondence, manuscripts, printed material, and personal and family papers documenting the life and work of American author and editor William Rose Benét. The collection spans the years 1847 to 1957, with the bulk of the collection dating from roughly 1900 to 1950.
Collection material is chiefly in English; with some material in French, Italiana, Russian, and Hebrew.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: Organized into five series: I. Correspondence, 1897-1955. II. Family Correspondence, 1883-1956. III. Writings, 1895-1957. IV. Printed Appearances of Writings by William Rose Benét, 1904-1950. V. Personal and Family Papers, 1847-1950.

relatedmaterial.head: Related Materials
relatedmaterial.p: Material by or relating to William Rose Benét acquired by the library from other Benét family sources can be located in the Benét Family Papers (YCAL MSS 1107). Material by or relating to William Rose Benét acquired by the library from non-family sources is located in the Benét Family Collection (YCAL MSS 1108). Additional material by or relating to William Rose Benét can also be found in the Stephen Vincent Benét and Rosemary Benét Papers (YCAL MSS 1046).

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: Organized into three subseries: General Correspondence, First Name Only, and Third Party Correspondence. General Correspondence is arranged alphabetically by correspondent and chronologically within files. First Name Only is arranged alphabetically within letter general files. Third Party Correspondence is arranged alphabetically.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Series I. Correspondence consists chiefly of single letters and small groups of incoming personal and professional correspondence to William Rose Benét and typescript carbons of Benét's outgoing letters to others. A significant amount of the General Correspondence in the series relates to Benét's editorial work on the Saturday Review (1923-1950) and other projects.

There are letters from many English-language authors and literary critics of the first half of the twentieth century, as well as from friends, publishers, editors of journals and newspapers, literary and cultural organizations, and academic institutions. Larger files can be found for poets Leonard Bacon, Sara Bard Field (and her husband Charles Erskine Scott Wood), Jeremy Ingalls, and Leonora Speyer, the law firm of Coudert Brothers, Christopher and Helen Morley, Rae Dalven, and colleagues at the Saturday Review . Other correspondents include W. H. Auden, John Berryman, Elizabeth Bishop, Thomas Caldecot Chubb, E. E. Cummings, John Dos Passos, Robert Frost, H. D., Robinson Jeffers, Sinclair Lewis, Marianne Moore, Ezra Pound, and Sara Teasdale.

A noteworthy component of the Correspondence series are letters to Benét's second wife, the poet Elinor Wylie. Correspondents include Willa Cather, Ford Maddox Ford, Charles Frederick Harrold, Aldous Huxley, Edith Sitwell, Hans Trausil, Edith Wharton, and Virginia Woolf. Files containing letters to Wylie exclusively are noted (to Elinor Wylie) in the folder description. The same descriptive strategy applies to the files containing letters to Marjorie Flack.

The Third Party Correspondence subseries consists of the loose third party correspondence in the series. Most likely these letters came into Benét's possession as enclosures and, over time, were separated from the original letters.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: Organized into two subseries: General Correspondence and Other Family Letters. General Correspondence is arranged alphabetically first by correspondent (sender) and then by recipient. Letters are arranged chonologically within files. Other Family Letters are arranged alphabetically.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Series II. Family Correspondence consists chiefly of letters between members of the Benét and Rose families. Large files can be found: between William Rose Benét and his mother, Frances Rose Benét, his father, James Walker Benét, and his sister, Laura Benét; to William Rose Benét from his three children, James Benét, Frances Rosemary (Benét) Dawson, and Kathleen Anne (Benét) Fry; and from William Rose Benét to his maternal grandmother, M. L. Rose, and his spouses, Teresa Frances (Thomson) Benét and Elinor Wylie.

Letters to and from in-laws can also be found here. There are letters with Kathleen and Charles Gilman Norris, for example, in-laws through Benét's marriage to Teresa Frances Thomson, and with members of the Hoyt family, in-laws through Benét's marriage to Elinor Wylie. In additon, there are third-party letters from non-family members.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: Organized into two subseries: Writings and Editorial Projects of William Rose Benét and Writings of Others. Writings of William Rose Benét are arranged aphabetically by title or heading. Writings of Others is arranged alphabetically by author.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Series III. Writings includes manuscript writings by Benét, material relating to editorial projects to which Benét contributed, and writings by others. Printed versions of individual works by Benét with autograph manuscript corrections can be found here, otherwise printed versions of writings by Benét are filed in Series IV.

The manuscripts of William Rose Benét consist chiefly of drafts of poems and other shorter works. Research material, notes, scenarios, proofs, and production-related material, such as publicity and correspondence, can also be found. Corrected and multiple drafts are common for many titles, showing the evolution of particular texts.

William Rose Benét is probably best known for his editorial work and poetry. In addition to his long-standing (1923-1950) position with the Saturday Review , Benét contributed to several compilations of English-language poetry and literature. The Writings series includes drafts and other material for unspecified "Anthologies" and for Fifty Poets: An American Auto-Anthology (1933). Drafts and other material relating to individual poems by Benét can be found by title in the alphabetical run of writings or in a group preserved under the supplied heading, [Poems]. Material can also be found for three poetry collections dating from the 1940s, Day of Deliverance:A Book of Poems in Wartime (1944), The Dust Which Is God (1941), a book of autobiographical verse for which Benét was awarded the Pulitzer Prize in poetry in 1942, and The Stairway of Surprise (1948).

In addition to poetry, Benét authored book reviews, essays, introductions, lectures and addresses, plays, and short stories. There is also material for two unpublished novels, "The Gilded Man" and "The Living Miranda."
There are also a good number of works by family members, both drafts and printed versions, and by others, some of which were no doubt sent to hared with Benét in his capacity as an editor.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: Organized into three subseries: Individual Titles (In Periodicals), Clippings, and Other. Each subseries is arranged alphabetically by title or supplied heading.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Series IV. Printed Appearances of Writings by William Rose Benét includes clippings of individual works, full issues of periodicals containing work(s) by Benét, and other printed versions of works.

There are examples of early work by Benét, written as an undergraduate while at Yale College, but most of the work found here includes short forms published in American magazines and newspapers from the early 1930s until 1950. Types of work include poems, book reviews, articles and essays, and short stories.

Benét served as an editor at the Saturday Review from 1923 until his death in 1950, and the series includes long runs of clippings from columns that appeared in the journal. The two columns, "The Phoenix Nest" and "Round About Parnassus," include poems and discussion of literary and other topics. Usually attributed directly to Benét, the "The Phoenix Nest" is sometimes attributed to "The Phoenician."

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: Organized into seven subseries: Artwork, Clippings, Financial and Legal Records, Other Family Papers, Photographs, Printed Material, and Other Material. Each subseries is arranged alphabetically.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Series V. Personal and Family Papers includes artwork, clippings, financial and legal records, photographs, and printed and other material. Artwork features drawings by William Rose Benét dating circa 1904 through the late 1940s. Artwork includes pencil and pen-and-ink sketches and illustrations for college magazines. There are also loose drawings and a sketchbook by Benét's friend, the artist Henry Martyn Hoyt, brother of his second wife Elinor Wylie, as well as a painting, "The End of the World," by Wylie.

Clippings in this series concern William Rose Benét, Benét's literary work, family members, and other topics. Financial and legal records include publication-related records, such as contracts and royalty statements, and personal financial information. In addition, there is material relating to the estates of several family members. Photographs are subdivided for prints of William Rose Benét, his family, other people, and places.

Finally, there is a variety of printed and other emphemera in the collection relating to Benét's personal life and professional activities. There are childhood school materials, calenders and diaries, a run of notebooks and manuscript notes, and scrapbooks.
Additional material relating specifically to the estate of Elinor Wylie can be found in the correspondence file for the law firm of Coudert Brothers in Series I.
